‚úÖ How many objects will be created

String str = "hello";
str.concat("hi");

->str.concat("hi") creates a new string object on the heap.
->String in Java is immutable, meaning once created, it cannot be changed.
->str.concat("hi") returns a new String "hellohi", but you didn‚Äôt assign it to any variable.
->So the original str still refers to "hello".
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
String str = "hello";
str=str.concat("hi");

Then, 3 objects were created: 
1 ->hello-stringpool,
1-hi->stringpool,
1- heap as contact
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
‚úÖ How to Resolve API Response Slowness
üìå Database Optimisation
    ‚Ä¢ Ensure proper indexes are created on the fields used in WHERE, JOIN, ORDER BY, and GROUP BY.
    ‚Ä¢ Avoid using SELECT *; fetch only the required columns.
    ‚Ä¢ Optimise queries and check execution plans to identify slow operations.
    ‚Ä¢ Use caching (Redis, Memcached, etc.) for frequently accessed or read-only data.
üì¶ Payload Optimisation
    ‚Ä¢ Avoid returning large payloads.
    ‚Ä¢ Implement pagination for list APIs.
    ‚Ä¢ Remove unnecessary metadata or nested objects from the response.
‚ö° Code & Logic Optimization
    ‚Ä¢ Identify and refactor complex logic or blocking code.
    ‚Ä¢ Use asynchronous / non-blocking calls where applicable.
    ‚Ä¢ Optimise loops and redundant computations inside the API.
    ‚Ä¢ Profile and monitor performance hotspots.
üõ†Ô∏è Infrastructure & API Design
    ‚Ä¢ Scale API servers horizontally (load balancing, auto-scaling).
    ‚Ä¢ Enable connection pooling for DB/API calls.
    ‚Ä¢ Use circuit breakers, bulkheads, and retries for external API calls.
    ‚Ä¢ Apply rate limiting and request throttling to prevent overload.
üóÇÔ∏è Caching Strategies
    ‚Ä¢ Use application-level caching (in-memory / distributed).
    ‚Ä¢ Implement HTTP caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control).
    ‚Ä¢ Cache DB queries or API responses where freshness is not critical.
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
* Connection pooling:  Is a technique where your application keeps a set (pool) of ready-to-use database connections instead of creating 
  a new one for every request.
  When the application starts, it creates a small number of database connections and stores them in a pool.
  When request comes Instead of creating a new DB connection, the app borrows one from the pool.
  Once done, the connection is returned to the pool (not closed). Now it‚Äôs available for another request.
  If traffic increases and more connections are needed, the pool can expand (up to a configured max-pool-size).

